<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Unmei wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I have issues with including Arcane Rune in these computations though - it's a fairly effective spell that makes the other spells look better because they get averaged in with it and disguises how sucky they really are.
<br />

<br />
Frankly, if they gave us runes of the values I mention above, I'd be fine with Arcane Rune not stacking with one or the other of our other rune lines because we wouldn't have to use both to get an appreciable increase in durability.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, the other runes suck.  Still, they stack: you can toss all 3 runes up if you really need the runeage, and use 1 when you don't.
<br />

<br />
The real problem with my analysis is that it compares current runing to runing before PoP.  And runing before pop wasn't ... that useful.
<br />

<br />
Second, since those runes came out, mana regen has shot up hugely.  Compare Kunark mana regen to today's mana regen.  Blasting heals out is now practical, and mobs are balanced against it: runes aren't blasted out, they are pre-buffed.  In Kunark you might get healed every 20 seconds.  Today you get healed every 4.  A rune that was good backwhen you got healed every 20 seconds, even if it scales with heals, isn't very good when you get healed every 4 seconds.  It becomes, as you notice, nothing more than a speed bump.
<br />

<br />
One might want to compare rune sizes to sustained healing rates today and in the Kunark era, rather than blast healing rates between L 60 and L 70.
<br />

<br />
Lastly, runes are HP-over-cap.  Back in Kunark, 800 HP-over-cap was a huge pile of HPs, compared to the HP players had.  Today, I suspect 3000 HP-over-cap may be much smaller.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
